explanation:
For each symbol: 

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro that yields the impl pointer from the token. Needed to know if this operation can have side effects or can fail/return NULL (i.e. whether the subsequent code is reachable/necessary).
- OS_impl_filehandle_table: The table indexed by the macro; its contents determine what impl->fd and impl->selectable are at runtime (affects reachability and behavior of later branches).
- OS_impl_file_internal_record_t: Definition (fields fd and selectable) is required to know what state is read/used by the function and whether reading these fields has observable effects.
- OS_object_token_t: Type/semantics of the token affect how OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET behaves and whether the token can represent invalid entries (influence dead-ness of code handling bad entries).
- OS_SockAddr_t: Defines AddrData and ActualLength used to compute slen and the slen != ActualLength branch; needed to determine if that branch can ever be removed safely.
- struct sockaddr: sa_family is switched on; required to know possible runtime families and whether certain switch cases are reachable.
- struct sockaddr_in / struct sockaddr_in6: Size values determine slen; needed to assess whether the slen vs ActualLength comparison and the AF_INET6 case are meaningful.
- AF_INET / AF_INET6: Family constants used in the switch; needed to determine which branches compile/execute and thus whether any case is dead code.
- OS_NETWORK_SUPPORTS_IPV6: Compile-time macro controlling inclusion of AF_INET6 case; required to know whether the code for IPv6 is present and potentially dead.
- connect: Syscall invoked that has strong side effects (initiates connection). Understanding its behavior/possible return values is essential to decide if subsequent handling is necessary or dead.
- errno: Global error indicator set by connect; needed because decision between immediate error handling and EINPROGRESS path depends on errno content.
- EINPROGRESS: Specific errno value checked; required to determine reachability of the select/waiting path.
- OS_DEBUG: Debug-print macro used in the error path; needed to determine whether that call is a side effect (observable) or a no-op (which would affect whether its removal is dead).
- strerror: Used with OS_DEBUG to produce a string; its side effects and use determine if the debug branch has observable effects.
- OS_SelectSingle_Impl: Called to wait for writability when connect returns EINPROGRESS. Its semantics (blocking, timeout handling, observable side effects) determine whether the select/wait code is required.
- OS_STREAM_STATE_WRITABLE: Bitmask used to test select result; needed to interpret OS_SelectSingle_Impl results and decide if the writable-checking code is necessary.
- selectable (field of OS_impl_file_internal_record_t): Controls whether OS_SelectSingle_Impl is invoked. Required to decide if the selectable==false path makes the select call dead or necessary.
- getsockopt: Called to read SO_ERROR after select; its semantics and return values determine whether that check is required or could be removed.
- SOL_SOCKET / SO_ERROR: Constants used by getsockopt; needed to know what option is read and whether reading it is observable/necessary.
- OS_SUCCESS / OS_ERROR / OS_ERR_BAD_ADDRESS / OS_ERROR_TIMEOUT: Return-code constants used throughout. Required to determine whether certain assignments/branches are meaningful to program behavior (i.e., whether returning different codes would change observable behavior).

These symbols together provide the runtime and compile-time information needed to decide whether any executed operation or branch in OS_SocketConnect_Impl has no observable effect and thus could be considered dead code under the MISRA dead-code rule.
